prj:ScienceGoal.prj:name: G14.2-south
prj:ScienceGoal.prj:note: Mosaic of 113 pointings to cover the southern filaments of the IRDC G14.225-0.506

prj:TechnicalJustification.prj:justificationText: We plan to use the correlator configured to operate in spectral line mode and dual polarization with 4 basebands, two of them placed in the LSB and two in the USB. The correlator is chosen to cover the C18O(1-0) line and other tracers of low-density gas (13CO(1-0)) as well as dense gas tracers such as CS(2-1), C34S(2-1), SO 3(2)-2(1), and 34SO 3(2)-2(1). We will use three basebands with two spectral windows each with a bandwidth of 58.594 MHz and a spectral resolution of 0.16 km/s to observe the proposed molecular lines. A spectral resolution of 0.16 km/s is needed to resolve the kinematics of the gas falling into the filaments and inflowing motions within the filaments themseleves. A fourth baseband of 1.875 GHz of bandwidth will be use to obtain an image of the continuum emission from the line free channels.

We plan to use ALMA in the compact configuration (C36-1n) at band 3 to perform a mosaic of 113 pointings toward the southern filaments of the Infrared Dark Cloud G14.2. The angular resolution, 3", is appropiate to resolve filaments, hubs, and striations. In particular, at the source distance of 1.98 kpc, we will trace the same spatial scales as the B213 filament in the Taurus molecular cloud. In addition, given the complex morphology of this filamentary system, we request the ACA-7m array to cover a wide range of spatial scales, which is necessary to trace filaments and the gas falling into them.

Because our main goal is to study the kinematics of the low-density gas using C18O(1-0) and 13CO(1-0), the sensitivity has been estimated based on our IRAM 30m data of C18O line, which is much weaker. The main beam temperature in the faintest regions is ~1K. Using a typical filament width of 10", we exect a line intensity in the 3" beam of 0.1 Jy/beam (taking into account the differences in spectral resolution as the IRAM 30m data has 0.6 km/s while the proposed observations are at a resolution of 0.16 km/s). The spectral resolution of 0.16 km/s is needed to to disentangle the kinematics of the gas within fillaments and falling into the them. Thus, in order to detect the line with a signal-to-noise ratio > 3 we need to achieve a sensitivity per pointing in the proposed mosaic of 26 mJy/beam. Therefore, the total observing time requested to perform a 113-pointing mosaic in the southern filaments with the 12m-array is 6.12 hours. Since we are adding the ACA-7m array we additionally need 12.39 hours, resulting in a total observing time of 18.58 hours, including system defined claibration and overheads.

We are aware that the project exceeds the maximum data rate allowed of 12MB/s. A slightly higher data rate (18.52 MB/s) is required in order to observe with high spectral resolution the selected transitions, necessary to image the gas kinematics.

prj:ScienceGoal.prj:name: G14.2-north
prj:ScienceGoal.prj:note: Mosaic of 99 pointings to cover the northern filaments of the IRDC G14.225-0.506

prj:TechnicalJustification.prj:justificationText: We plan to use the correlator configured to operate in spectral line mode and dual polarization, with 4 basebands, two of them placed in the LSB and two in the USB. The correlator is chosen to cover the C18O(1-0) line and other tracers of low-density gas (13CO(1-0)) as well as dense gas tracers such as CS(2-1), C34S(2-1), SO 3(2)-2(1), and 34SO 3(2)-2(1). We will use three basebands with two spectral windows each with a bandwidth of 58.594 MHz and a spectral resolution of 0.16 km/s to cover the proposed molecular lines. A spectral resolution of 0.16km/s is needed to resolve the kinematics of the gas falling into the filaments and inflowing motions within filaments. A fourth baseband of 1.875 GHz will be use to obtain an image of the continuum emission from the line free channels.

We plan to use ALMA in the compact configuratio C36-1n at band 3 to perform a mosaic of 99 pointings in G14.2 to map the northern part of the filamentary network. The angular resolution, 3", is appropiate to resolve filaments, hubs, and striations. In particular, at the source distance, we will trace the same spatial scales as the B213 filament in the Taurus molecular cloud.
In addition, given the complex morphoogy of this filamentary system we request the ACA-7m array to cover a wide range of spatial scales, whic is necessary to trace the filaments and the gas falling into them.

Because our main goal is to study the kinematics of the low-density gas using C18O(1-0) and 13CO(1-0) lines, the sensitivity has been estimated based on our IRAM 30m data of C18O. The main beam temperature in the faintest regions is ~1K. Using a typical filament width of 10", we expect a line intensity in the 3" beam of 0.1Jy/beam, taking into account the differences in spectral resolution as the IRAM 30m data has 0.6 km/s while the proposed observations are at a resolution of 0.16 km/s. Thus, in order to detect the line with a signal-to-noise ratio > 3 we need to achieve a sensitivity in each pointing of the poposed mosaic of 26 mJy/beam. We point out that the requested spectral resolution of 0.16 km/s is essential to disentangle the gas motions within filaments, expected to have velocity differences along a filament of less than 1 km/s.
Therefore, the total observing time requested to perform the mosaic of 99 pointings toward the northern filaments with the 12m array is 5.22 hours. Since we are additing the ACA-7m array we additionally need 10.44 hours, resulting in a total observing time of 15.66 hours, including system defined calibration and overheads.

We are aware that the project exceeds the maximum data rate allowed of 12 MB/s. A slightly higher data rate (18.52 MB/s) is required in order to observe with high spectral resolution data the selected molecular transitions, necessary to image in detail the gas kinematics.

prp:ObsProposal.prp:abstract: Although filaments appear to be ubiquitous structures within molecular clouds, their formation mechanism is far from well understood. In a scenario of global, multi-scale gravitational contraction of molecular clouds, filaments and clumps are all in a state of gravitational contraction, rather than being virialized structures as suggested in turbulence-supported models. In this case of multi-scale gravitational contraction, main filaments gain mass from the surrounding material, which rains onto them through smaller elongated structures perpendicular to them. With this proposal we aim to test this scenario by studying the kinematics of the gas surrounding main filaments at different spatial scales, hence requiring both high sensitivity and angular resolution, a performance which can only be achieved with ALMA. We propose to perform a mosaic using low-density gas tracers of a well-studied infrared-dark cloud consisting of two prominent hub-filament systems. These observations will constitute a crucial test for basic theories of molecular cloud dynamics and filament formation.
